nfobox NCAA team season\n  |year=1984\n  |team=Michigan State Spartans\n  |image = Michigan State Spartans script.svg\n  |image_size = 120\n  |conference=Big Ten Conference\n  |short_conf=Big Ten\n  |record=6\u20136\n  |conf_record=5\u20134\n  |CoachRank=\n  |APRank=\n  |head_coach=[[George Perles]]\n  |hc_year=2nd\n  |def_coach=[[Nick Saban]]\n  |dc_year = 2nd\n  |mvp=\n  |captain=Jim Morrissey\n  |stadium=[[Spartan Stadium (East Lansing)|Spartan Stadium]] <br> (Capacity: 76,000) \n  |champion=\n  |bowl=[[1984 Cherry Bowl|Cherry Bowl]]\n  |bowl_result=L 6-10 vs [[Army Black Knights Football|Army]]\n}}\n{{1984 Big Ten football standings}}\nThe '''1984 Michigan State Spartans football team''' represented [[Michigan State University]] in the [[1984 Big Ten Conference football season]]. In their second season under head coach [[George Perles]], the Spartans compiled a 6\u20136 overall record (5\u20134 against Big Ten opponents) and finished in a tie for sixth place in the [[Big Ten Conference]].<ref name=CFDW>{{cite news|title=Michigan State Yearly Results (1980-1984)|publisher=David DeLassus|work=College Football Data Warehouse|accessdate=July 18, 2015|url=http://www.cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/active/m/michigan_state/1980-1984_yearly_results.php}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=2015 Michigan State Football Media Guide|publisher=Michigan State University|page=147|accessdate=July 4, 2016|url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/msu/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/2015-16/misc_non_event/msu-media-guide-135-186-histor.pdf}}</ref>\n\nSix Spartans were recognized by the [[Associated Press]] (AP) and/or the [[United Press International]] (UPI) on the [[1984 All-Big Ten Conference football team]]: linebacker [[Jim Morrissey]] (AP-2; UPI-1); defensive back [[Phil Parker]] (UPI-1); running back Carl Butler (UPI-2); center Mark Napolitan (AP-2); defensive lineman Kelly Quinn (AP-2; UPI-2); and placekicker and punter Ralf Mojsienenko (AP-2; UPI-2).<ref name=AP>{{cite news|title=Byars Unanimous All-Big Ten Choice|newspaper=The Blade (Toledo)|date=November 28, 1984|page=36|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1350&dat=19841128&id=IW4xAAAAIBAJ&sjid=wwIEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6808,3576009}}</ref><ref name=UPI>{{cite news|title=1984 All-Big Ten Football team|publisher=UPI.com|date=November 19, 1984|url=http://www.upi.com/Archives/1984/11/19/1984-All-Big-Ten-Football-team/1750469688400/}}</ref>\n\n==Schedule==\n{{CFB schedule\n| rankyear = 1984\n| poll = AP\n| timezone = Eastern\n\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 8\n| time = \n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| away = y\n| rank = \n| opponent = [[1984 Colorado Buffaloes football team|Colorado]]\n| site_stadium = [[Folsom Field]]\n| site_cityst = [[Boulder, Colorado|Boulder, CO]]\n| tv = \n| score = 24-21\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 15\n| time = \n| w/l = l\n| nonconf = y\n| rank = \n| opponent = [[1984 Notre Dame Fighting Irish football team|Notre Dame]]\n| gamename = [[Megaphone Trophy]]\n| site_stadium = [[Spartan Stadium (East Lansing, Michigan)|Spartan Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[East Lansing, Michigan|East Lansing, MI]]\n| tv = \n| score = 20-24\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 22\n| time = \n| w/l = l\n| away = y\n| rank = \n| opponent = [[1984 Illinois Fighting Illini football team|Illinois]]\n| site_stadium = [[Memorial Stadium (Champaign)|Memorial Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Champaign, IL]]\n| tv = \n| score = 7-40\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 29\n| time = \n| w/l = l\n| rank = \n| opponent = [[1984 Purdue Boilermakers football team|Purdue]]\n| site_stadium = Spartan Stadium\n| site_cityst = East Lansing, MI\n| tv = \n| score = 10-13\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 6\n| time = \n| w/l = w\n| away = y\n| rank = \n| opponent = [[1984 Michigan Wolverines football team|Michigan]]\n| opprank = 13\n| gamename = [[Paul Bunyan Trophy]]\n| site_stadium = Michigan Stadium\n| site_cityst = Ann Arbor, MI\n| tv = \n| score = 19-7\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule