plete [[The Ritz Hotel, London#The Palm Court|Palm Court]] orchestra platform),<ref name=HPC /> and the backup mechanism of [[Tower Bridge]].<ref name=Emmerson /> It was also used to supply [[fire hydrant]]s, mostly those inside buildings. The water, pumped straight from the Thames, was heated in winter to prevent freezing.<ref name=HPC />\n\n==Pumping stations==\n[[File:Wapping Hydraulic Power Station 1.jpg|thumb|Wapping Hydraulic Power Station]]\nThe pressure was maintained at a nominal {{convert|800|psi|MPa}} (55 BAR) by five hydraulic power stations, originally driven by [[coal]]-fired [[steam engine]]s.<ref name=HPC /> These were at:\n* Falcon Wharf Pumping Station at [[Bankside Power Station|Bankside]], east of [[Blackfriars Bridge]] on the south bank of the River Thames (opened in 1883)<ref name=Skinner>{{cite book|last1=Skinner|first1=Steve|title=Hydraulic Fluid Power - A Historical Timeline|date=2014|isbn=9781291676891|page=77}}</ref>\n* Kensington Court and Millbank (1887)<ref name=Skinner /> later (1911) replaced by a station in Grosvenor Road<ref name=Morgan>{{cite journal|last1=Morgan|first1=Roger|title=Watery Death of Electricity's Rival|journal=New Scientist|date=28 July 1977|pages=221\u2013223}}</ref>\n* [[Wapping Hydraulic Power Station|Wapping Hydraulic Pumping Station]] (est. 1890),<ref name=Skinner /> using the defunct [[Tower Subway]] to carry pipes under the Thames (closed on 30 June 1977, the last to be used)<ref name=Morgan />\n* City Road Basin on the [[Regent's Canal]] in [[Islington]] (1893),<ref name=Skinner /> later used as the Marico furniture factory<ref name=Morgan />\n* Renforth Pump House ([[Rotherhithe]], [[Canada Water]]) (opened in 1904),<ref name=Skinner /> now residential accommodation\n\nShort-term storage was provided by [[hydraulic accumulator]]s, which were large vertical pistons loaded with heavy weights.  \n\n== Cross-River Thames mains ==\nThe mains crossed the River Thames via [[Vauxhall Bridge]], [[Waterloo Bridge]] and [[Southwark Bridge]] and via the [[Rotherhithe Tunnel]] as well as the [[Tower Subway]].<ref name=Mike>{{cite web|title=London's Hydraulic Power|url=http://engwonders.byethost9.com/e047.html|website=Mike's Engineering Wonders: Vintage Pages from the 1930s|accessdate=1 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Decline ==\nThe system pumped 6.5 million gallons of water each week in 1893; this grew to 32 million gallons in 1933. \n\nFrom about 1904, business began to decline as [[electric power]] became more popular. The company began to replace its [[steam engine]]s with [[electric motor]]s from 1923. At its peak, the network consisted of {{convert|180|mi|km}} of pipes, and the total power output was about {{convert|7000|hp|MW}}.  \n\nThe system finally closed in June 1977.  The company, as a UK statutory authority, had the legal right to dig up the public highways to install and maintain its pipe network. This made it attractive to [[Mercury Communications]] (a subsidiary of [[Cable & Wireless plc|Cable & Wireless]]) who bought the company and used the pipes as [[telecommunications]] [[Electrical conduit|ducts]].<ref name=Emmerson /><ref name=Mercury>{{cite journal|title=Mercury plugs into hydraulic ducts|journal=New Scientist|date=21 March 1985|issue=1448|page=7|url=https://books.google.com/?id=wVBOlTz4-ycC&pg=PA7&lpg=PA7&dq=%22Wharves+and+Warehouses+Steam+Power+and+Hydraulic+Pressure+Company%22#v=onepage&q=%22Wharves%20and%20Warehouses%20Steam%20Power%20and%20Hydraulic%20Pressure%20Company%22&f=false|accessdate=3 January 2016|last1=Information|first1=Reed Business}}</ref> Wapping Hydraulic Power Station, the last of the five to close, later became an arts centre and restaurant.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Liverpool Hydraulic Power Company]]\n* [[Manchester Hydraulic Power]]\n\n==References==\n{{notelist}}\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{cite book\n  |title=Hydraulic Power\n  |first=Ian |last=McNeil\n  |publisher=Longman Group\n  |year=1972\n  |isbn=978-0-582-12797-5\n  |re